title: For Sale:  Kel Tec SUB-2000 40 S&W Carbine KelTec 2000 Rifle
postcontent:
This auction is for a new black Kel-Tec Sub 2000 G22 folding carbine, chambered in .40 S&W with a 16.1" barrel. It accepts all Glock Model 22 magazines, and comes with one 10-round G22 mag. This gun is idea when you need the firepower of a long gun but need something light weight and very compact. It can be carried/concealed in just about anything and deployed instantly. Using readily available Glock 22 mags, this carbine makes for an ideal self-defense gun that can be taken just about anywhere with ease.

The SUB-2000 has a greatly extended range compared to a handgun.  The superior precision is also very useful against small or partially covered targets at shorter range.  The amount of training to master the SUB-2000 is only a fraction of that required for a handgun.  This is an excellent choice for a vehicle gun, backpack gun, or anytime you might need something more than a handgun but do not have a lot of room and need something light and compact.

The bolt can be locked in the rear position by the operating handle.  The main safety is of protected push bolt type disconnecting the trigger bar and interlocking the hammer and sear.  By rotating the barrel upwards and back, the SUB 2000 can be reduced to a size of 16" x 7" to facilitate secure storage and utilize the internal deployment lock which is operated by a proprietary key.  The rear sight is of aperture type and the fluorescent front sight can be adjusted for windage and elevation.  The SUB-2000 can easily be disassembled without tools for cleaning or inspection.

I have a brand new all-metal Bushmaster XM 15 Optics Ready Carbine with 16" chrome-lined A4-style barrel for sale. Not "brand new with only 100 rounds through it" but totally new. I've never even loaded it! This is a quality factory-built Bushmaster, and not a cheaper DPMS product, or a plastic Carbon 15, or someone's garage build, and a complete ready-to-use package for less than some are selling their used, base model rifle.

Gun comes with:
-Factory box (if you want it)
-2 metal 30-round Bushmaster magazines (comes with 1 in store)
-Empty chamber indicator flag
-Lock and key
-Sling
-2 rail risers in case you want to use a big scope
-Warranty
-Owner's manual
-and whatever extra paperwork/coupons/etc are included normally

It is factory built with the receiver-length picatinny rail, 6-position adjustable stock, A2 flash suppressor on a threaded barrel, bayonet lug, and sling swivels. And unlike most modern AR's, the calibers are stamped on the mag well so you know it accepts BOTH .223 AND 5.56 ammunition, whatever you can find to use - no guessing that the NATO rounds MIGHT go boom without your gun going BOOM!

Also included is:
-A brand new (in the unopened box) BSA 42 mm red-dot scope sight with built-on sun shade (can include UTG red dot if you prefer)
-60 rounds of new brass PMC X-tac 5.56 55 gr FMJ (perfect military round for this barrel)
-A brand new Tapco Intrafuse AR spanner wrench with a mil-spec castle wrench, receiver extension removal wrench, and A1/A2 flash suppressor wrench. It is manganese phosphate coated for durability, and has a lifetime warranty
-A brand new weather-resistant ammo box large enough for all the extras to fit in
-A brand new Midway USA padded tactical range bag with 4 velcro pockets to hold 30 round magazines, a middle velcro pocket, and a long zipper pocket.  It has handles and an adjustable strap on the back to carry by hand or over your shoulder.

With this complete AR 15 package you have everything you need, and can get it sighted in on the range and have some fun banging away without having to wait a couple months to find some clean ammo, or pay $1 a round.

The base model MSRP on the rifle is $1,391.48, and with this deal you avoid taxes, fees, and snoopy government agents.  I saw these at the last gun show going for around $1600 without any extras, so I'm listing it at $1500 (with ammo, red dot, wrench, bag, and ammo box included).  Face-to-face cash sale, prefer you have a CCW but not required.

I have a brand new rail-mountable tactical laser/light combo with pressure switches I can throw in for an extra $40 (normally $50 plus tax).

I'll just laugh at you, and probably put your idiocy and name on display in my next gun article for the world to laugh at you.  Ditto if you e-mail me with any other complaints or gripes without actually displaying any interest in the rifle.

title: For Sale:  FS/FT Korea Era US Military M3 IR Sniper Scope
location: St. Michael, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack(nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it would be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.

Of course all cash is always nice. FTF meet. Leave your name and number or I will not get back to you.

Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Korea Era IR M3 Sniper scope
location: St. Michael, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
For sale and maybe partial trade is my Korea Era Us military Sniper Scope. Known officially as: M3, sniperscope, infrared, set no. 1, 20,000 volts. Made by american optical co. Buffalo, NY 6-23-51. Made to be mounted on a special M1 carbine known as the M2 carbine making the whole setup a M3. 

Very good condition. Really nice for how old it is. How does it compare to others? I don't know. I've never seen one that wasn't in a book or on the internet. This is the only one I have ever seen. Very rare, very cool piece of American Military History.

What is there and what isn't. This comes with the IR scope, IR Light, Foregrip/ Handle with the trigger, power transformer box, all necessary original wiring, 1 tube, original rubberized backpack(nice), and original chest. As far as what is missing? I'm really no expert but I think there was a tool set and more tubes. These are not there. And of course no .30 carbine. No rust anywhere and looks to be the original finish. Some scratches on the scope but not bad. A little corrosion on a small copper piece behind the light source. And it looks like the red filter is a little rough. The outside plastic of the light source is fine, its the red filter inside. I have not taken this apart or tried to clean any of it. 

Because this is so rare I did not want auction it, I wanted a lot of people to have a shot at owning it. Same with gun broker. I found it in Mn I would like a collector in MN to give it a good home. So I figured the only fair way to do it would be to take offers. So, if you want it, take a shot at it and email me your best offer. If you know what it is, you know what its worth, and how often you can find one.

As far as trades go... I might, might, take one of the following as partial trade with cash. 1. Ruger .44 carbine semi-auto. Prefer older tube fed. 2. Ruger No. 1 in 270 win, 280 rem, 30.06 or 303 brit. 3. HK usp Tactical all black. Of course these guns must be nice.
